Objective¶

The goal for this project is:
  • To create a machine learning model to predict if a customer from a bank would churn or not, according several features.

Database Information¶

  • Target Variable:

    • Exited: Whether the customer churned or not (1 for Yes, 0 for No).

  • Features:

    • CustomerId: A unique identifier for each customer.
    • Surname: The surname of the customer.
    • CreditScore: The credit score of the customer.
    • Geography: The country of the customer.
    • Gender: The gender of the customer.
    • Age: The age of the customer.
    • Tenure: The number of years the customer has been with the bank.
    • Balance: The account balance of the customer.
    • NumOfProducts: The number of products the customer has with the bank.
    • HasCrCard: Whether the customer has a credit card (1 for Yes, 0 for No).
    • IsActiveMember: Whether the customer is an active member (1 for Yes, 0 for No).
    • EstimatedSalary: The estimated salary of the customer.

Replacing the outliers with the median on each column using a Pipeline

In [189]:
from pyspark.ml import Transformer
from pyspark.ml.param.shared import HasInputCols, HasOutputCols
from pyspark import keyword_only
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, lit, when

class OutlierReplacer(Transformer, HasInputCols, HasOutputCols):
    @keyword_only
    def __init__(self, inputCols=None, outputCols=None):
        super(OutlierReplacer, self).__init__()
        kwargs = self._input_kwargs
        self.setParams(**kwargs)
    
    @keyword_only
    def setParams(self, inputCols=None, outputCols=None):
        kwargs = self._input_kwargs
        return self._set(**kwargs)
    
    def _transform(self, churn_raw):
        for inputCol in self.getInputCols():
            Q1, Q3 = churn_raw.approxQuantile(inputCol, [0.25, 0.75], 0)
            median = churn_raw.approxQuantile(inputCol, [0.5], 0)[0]
            IQR = Q3 - Q1
            lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
            upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
            
            churn_raw = churn_raw.withColumn(inputCol, 
                               when(
                                   (col(inputCol) < lower_bound) | (col(inputCol) > upper_bound), 
                                   lit(median)
                               ).otherwise(col(inputCol)))
        return churn_raw
In [190]:
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

# Assuming spark is your SparkSession and df is your DataFrame
# Define your input columns
inputCols = ["Age", "Balance", "EstimatedSalary", "CreditScore"]

# Instantiate the OutlierReplacer with the specified input columns
outlierReplacer = OutlierReplacer(inputCols=inputCols, outputCols=inputCols)

# Create the Pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[outlierReplacer])

# Fit the pipeline to the data
pipelineModel = pipeline.fit(churn_raw)

# Transform the data
data = pipelineModel.transform(churn_raw)

# Show the result
data.show()

from pyspark.ml.stat import Correlation
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler
import pandas as pd

# Assuming 'data' is your Spark DataFrame with the specified columns

# Assemble the numeric columns into a vector
assembler = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["Age", "Balance", "EstimatedSalary", "CustomerId", "HasCrCard", "Tenure", "CreditScore", "NumOfProducts", "IsActiveMember"], 
    outputCol="features"
)
vector_data = assembler.transform(data)

# Calculate correlations
matrix = Correlation.corr(vector_data, "features").head()

# Convert the dense matrix to a Pandas DataFrame
# Extract the numpy array from the dense matrix
correlation_matrix = matrix[0].toArray()

# Create a Pandas DataFrame with proper labels
column_labels = ["Age", "Balance", "EstimatedSalary", "CustomerId", "HasCrCard", "Tenure", "CreditScore", "NumOfProducts", "IsActiveMember"]
df_correlation = pd.DataFrame(correlation_matrix, index=column_labels, columns=column_labels)

# Print the correlation matrix
print(df_correlation)

Feature Transformation¶

We need to translate the values in string columns into numerical values.

In order to do so, we are going to encode categorical values using:

StringIndexer
OneHotEncoder

In [243]:
label_column = "Exited"

categoricalCols = [field for (field, dataType) in data.dtypes if ((dataType == "string") & (field != label_column))]
numericCols = [field for (field, dataType) in data.dtypes if ((dataType == "double") & (field != label_column))]

print (f"categorical columns: {categoricalCols}")
print (f"numerical columns: {numericCols}")

categorical columns: ['Geography', 'Gender']
numerical columns: ['CreditScore', 'Age', 'Tenure', 'Balance', 'NumOfProducts', 'HasCrCard', 'IsActiveMember', 'EstimatedSalary']

from pyspark.ml.feature import OneHotEncoder, StringIndexer

stringIndexer = StringIndexer(inputCols=categoricalCols, outputCols=indexOutputCols, handleInvalid="skip")

oheEncoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCols=indexOutputCols,outputCols=oheOutputCols)

Feature Assembling¶

It's finally time to assemble the features in one single vector, which is what the algorithm will expect, by using something called VectorAssembler.

As the "Exited" variable is the one we want to predict, all the other variables will be considered to build the list with required features:

In [248]:
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler

vecAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=assemblerInputs,outputCol="features")
In [249]:
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

test_pipeline = Pipeline(stages = [stringIndexer, oheEncoder, vecAssembler])
features_df = test_pipeline.fit(data).transform(data)
features_df.limit(2).toPandas()

4. Model Training¶

Here is the list of few classification algorithms from Spark ML we are going to try:

  • LogisticRegression
  • DecisionTreeClassifier
  • RandomForestClassifier
  • Gradient-boosted tree classifier
  • NaiveBayes
  • Linear Support Vector Machine

There are some points in the machine learning workflow were randomness takes place, for example during the sets splitting and some ML algorithms like RandomForest.

In order to make our experiments reproducible and get always the same results with the same data no matter how many times we execute our code, we are going to use a seed.

The seed is tipically a prime number.

In [250]:
seed=11
In [251]:
from pyspark.ml.classification import LogisticRegression
from pyspark.ml.classification import DecisionTreeClassifier
from pyspark.ml.classification import RandomForestClassifier
from pyspark.ml.classification import GBTClassifier
from pyspark.ml.classification import NaiveBayes
from pyspark.ml.classification import LinearSVC

lr = LogisticRegression(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features")
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features",seed=seed)
rf = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features",maxDepth=10,seed=seed)
gbt = GBTClassifier(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features",maxIter=10,seed=seed)
nb = NaiveBayes(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features")
svm = LinearSVC(labelCol="Exited", featuresCol="features")

classifiers = [lr,dt,rf,gbt,nb,svm]
classifiers

Let's create a pipeline for every classifier

In [252]:
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline

def create_pipeline(classifier):
    return Pipeline(stages = [stringIndexer, oheEncoder, vecAssembler, classifier])

pipelines = [create_pipeline(classifier) for classifier in classifiers]

5. Model Evaluation¶

We're going to evaluate our classification model by using MulticlassClassificationEvaluator

We're going to use the accuray metric.

In [253]:
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator

evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="Exited",  metricName="accuracy")

6. Model Selection¶

Now that the data is all set, let's split it into training and test. We can use a 80-20 ratio

In [254]:
(trainingData, testData) = data.randomSplit([0.8,0.2],seed=seed)

It's a good practice to keep the same distribution of 0's and 1's in the training set, and specially critical in unbalanced/skew datasets. This is called Stratified Train-Test Split

In [255]:
(trainingData1, testData1) = data.where("Exited=0").randomSplit([0.8,0.2],seed=seed)
(trainingData2, testData2) = data.where("Exited=1").randomSplit([0.8,0.2],seed=seed)

traininData = trainingData1.unionByName(trainingData2)
testData = testData1.unionByName(testData2)

Let's train all the classifiers

In [257]:
names = []
values = [] 
for model in models:
    prediction_df = model.transform(testData)
    accuracy = evaluator.evaluate(prediction_df)
    names.append(type(model.stages[-1]).__name__) # the algorithm is the last stage in the pipeline
    values.append(accuracy)

data = {'name':names,'accuracy':values,'model':models}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)
df.sort_values(by=['accuracy'], inplace=True, ascending=False)
